%X A gel-diffusion technique in which transport occurs across a thin agar membrane has been devised. This technique was used for pore-size calibration of a series of agar gels of various concentrations by measurement of hindrance to diffusion of human hemoglobin and southern bean mosaic virus particles. Pore radii calculated from independent restricted diffusion measurements of these two particle-species by use of a theoretical equation of were in very good agreement, and show that this equation provides a close approximation to the diffusional restriction occurring in these systems. Values of restricted diffusion coefficients in gels of various pore sizes were obtained from restricted diffusion measurements of four other proteins (rabbit [gamma]-globulin, human serum albumin, bovine serum albumin, and pancreatic ribonuclease). When these coefficients were extrapolated to conditions of infinite pore size (zero gel concentration) the values obtained agreed generally with reported values of the free diffusion coefficients for these proteins. Sharp differentiation in diffusional restriction on the basis of particle size and shape was demonstrated.

